# Architecture

```d2

overview: |md 
# High-level overview of the deployed infrastructure on Azure.|

direction: right

users: Users {
  shape: person
}

operator: Operator {
  shape: person
}

rg: Resource Group {
  style.fill: "#e8f4f8"
  style.stroke: "#0078d4"

  pip: Public IP & DNS {
    shape: cloud
    style.fill: "#cfe8fc"
    style.stroke: "#0078d4"
  }

  vnet: Virtual Network {
    shape: hexagon
    style.fill: "#dce9f5"
    style.stroke: "#0078d4"
  }

  vm: "Linux VM\n(CKAN, GitLab, Solr, PostgreSQL)" {
    shape: rectangle
    style.fill: "#fff4ce"
    style.stroke: "#f2a900"
  }

  kv: Key Vault {
    shape: stored_data
    style.fill: "#fce8d5"
    style.stroke: "#e05c00"
  }

  sa: "Storage Account\n(OpenTofu State)" {
    shape: cylinder
    style.fill: "#dff2db"
    style.stroke: "#107c10"
  }

  automation: "Automation Account\n(VM Scheduler)" {
    shape: step
    style.fill: "#e6f3ff"
    style.stroke: "#0078d4"
  }
}

notes: |md
## Notes
- The Key Vault stores deployment secrets such as the CKAN database password; Ansible reads them at runtime via the Azure CLI.
- OpenTofu state is bootstrapped locally on first apply, then migrated to the Storage Account backend.
- Ansible and OpenTofu both authenticate to Azure via `az login` / `az account set`.
- The Automation Account stops the VM at 7 PM EST and starts it at 7 AM EST daily to reduce costs.
|

users -> rg.pip: HTTPS
rg.pip -> rg.vnet
rg.vnet -> rg.vm
operator -> rg.vm: SSH / Ansible
operator -> rg.kv: Read secrets
operator -> rg.sa: OpenTofu state
rg.automation -> rg.vm: Start/Stop on schedule
